<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-263-958  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 263 958.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>DG Review  March 1990 v10 n9 p15(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Getting to &quot;No Problem&quot;. (connectivity, past, present and future)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Espe, Mark; Wellings, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The ultimate goal of the continuing computer revolution istransparent access to information.andP;  Studying the trends of therecent past and the presence leads to the conclusion that whenthis transparent access arrives it will do so in a package smallerand more complete than anything postulated in science fiction.andO;Microcomputers will continue to get smaller, data storage capacitywill continue to increase in relation to module size, and methodsof interconnecting systems will progress to the point whereconnectivity, once the main stumbling block to transparent access,becomes 'no problem'.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Future of ComputingConnectivityTransparencyInformation Resources ManagementData Management.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>